<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO JED</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan  3 10:56:01 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Jed,<br><br>
Just a few thoughts, as I don't have enough time to really get into the subject just yet, but here goes.<br><br>
Did you know that the protestor's actions directly and indirectly placed US Servicemen's lives in jeopardy?  They did, especially pertaining to the Jane Fonda trip to Hanoi.  This was readily known by the US Servicemen, and they quite simply, and very emphatically, resented the protestor's actions.<br><br>
The communists were against the war?  Since when?  They were against the US and South Vietnamese, and actively supplied the North Vietnamese, Pathet Loa, Kamor Rouge, and Viet Cong.  We couldn't touch Russian supply ships in Hanoi, but we could try bombing a bridge.  And the communists could rain rockets anywhere they liked, and nobody said a thing.  I think this was the biggest rub, none of  the protestors said a thing of the atrosities committed by the communists.<br><br>
You asked several questions.  I don’t have time to answer fully, but here’s a stab at a few.  <br><br>
Why were we there?  It started out as a  very simple idea, that we wanted to prevent a communist takeover.  It got very complex as the administrations changed.  It also got more complex as the administrations tried to explain it to the American public, and did very badly at it.  There were things that couldn’t be talked about in public too.  <br><br>
Why didn’t we, and don’t we, have anger against our government?  Perhaps we were closer to it than were you, and understood what was really happening better.  You should read the book by John Del Veccio entitled “For the sake of all living things” to get a better understanding of what it was all about.<br><br>
Did we have a right to be there?  Definitely!  We were invited, and had the rights under SEATO, as did the Australians, the Koreans, and others who fought there.<br><br>
Well, ‘got to go (other matters are pressing).  But this gives you some of my perspectives.<br>

